# Pinned gfortran compiler flags for the NONROAD Linux x86_64 build.
#
# Sourced by build.sh, by canonical-moves.def's %post, and by any future
# tooling that recompiles NONROAD. Single source of truth — Makefile.linux
# accepts FLGS from the environment when set so the values below
# determine what the binary actually contains.
#
# Background — the gfortran "near-zero" bug
# -----------------------------------------
# NONROAD/NR08a/SOURCE/readme.md warns that gfortran on some Linux
# platforms produces "incorrectly near-zero emission results for some
# equipment types". The upstream EPA recommendation is to use a
# different Fortran compiler. We don't have that option on the HPC
# system this work runs on, so we go all-in on gfortran with a flag
# set chosen to neutralize the most likely root causes.
#
# Hypotheses tried and current verdict
# ------------------------------------
#
# H1 -- Default real precision (-fdefault-real-8 -fdefault-double-8).
#   Originally listed as the strongest hypothesis (older commercial f77
#   defaulted to 8-byte reals; gfortran defaults to 4-byte). Tested and
#   REJECTED: NONROAD's source declares variables as `real*4` (4-byte)
#   throughout, while many call sites pass arguments using the implicit
#   default real type. With -fdefault-real-8 the implicit default
#   becomes 8-byte and gfortran emits dozens of "Type mismatch between
#   actual argument" warnings between callers (real(8)) and callees
#   (real(4)). Compilation succeeds but the resulting binary reads 4
#   bytes where 8 were written (or vice versa) at every such call
#   boundary -- a strict regression, not a fix.
#
# H2 -- Storage model: locals as SAVE'd (-fno-automatic).
#   F77 traditionally treated all locals as SAVE (retained across
#   calls); gfortran's default is the opposite (stack-allocated, fresh
#   each call). NONROAD has many accumulator-style locals that almost
#   certainly assume SAVE semantics; without -fno-automatic, those
#   accumulators get re-zeroed on every entry. This matches the
#   "near-zero emissions for some equipment types" symptom: equipment
#   categories that depend on a multi-call accumulation pathway zero
#   out, while categories with single-call computation paths look
#   normal. ENABLED.
#
# H3 -- Initialization (-finit-local-zero -finit-real=zero).
#   Belt-and-suspenders for any non-SAVE locals that the source assumed
#   were zero on first use without explicit DATA initialization. Cheap
#   insurance; cannot mask a real H2 bug because -fno-automatic gives
#   locals SAVE storage and -finit-* only fires on first entry.
#   ENABLED.
#
# H4 -- COMMON-block layout (-fno-align-commons).
#   gfortran can silently insert padding into COMMON blocks for
#   alignment; that is invisible at the source level but breaks any
#   code that reads/writes COMMON via raw record I/O or assumes a
#   contiguous layout. NONROAD has many large COMMON blocks. ENABLED.
#
# H5 -- Fixed-form line length (-ffixed-form -ffixed-line-length-132).
#   The source is fixed-form Fortran 77; the .f extension usually
#   triggers fixed-form parsing but some distros' gfortran configs
#   change the default. Pin both. ENABLED.
#
# H6 -- Implicit-typing strictness (-fimplicit-none).
#   Would flush out untyped variables. Tested and REJECTED: while most
#   source files have IMPLICIT NONE (116 of 119), spinit.f relies on
#   implicit typing and forcing the flag globally fails compilation
#   there.
#
# H7 -- Array-bounds + FP exception checking (-fcheck=all + -ffpe-trap).
#   Useful for diagnosing a specific failure but adds material runtime
#   overhead. Surfaced in FLAGS_AUDIT, not FLAGS_PRODUCTION.
#
# Static linking is also rejected: -static requires a static
# libgfortran which most distros do not ship, and dynamic linking is
# fine inside the Apptainer SIF where libgfortran is available at a
# pinned version. Builds outside the SIF that need a portable binary
# can override FC/FLGS at the build.sh invocation site.
#
# How to evolve this file:
#   - Bumping a flag is a deliberate cutover. The new SIF SHA256 lands
#     in canonical-image.lock; downstream characterization snapshots
#     taken against the old SHA become non-authoritative.
#   - If a specific equipment category cannot be made fidelity-correct
#     within the validation tolerance, the migration plan accepts
#     widened-tolerance documentation as a fallback. Record the
#     divergence in this file's tail, NOT silently in code.

# ----- Compiler -----
# gfortran is the only compiler available on the HPC this work targets.
# If a different compiler ever joins the toolchain, override FC at the
# build.sh invocation site, do not edit this default in-place.
FC="${FC:-gfortran}"

# ----- Production build flags -----
# Used for the binary baked into canonical-moves.sif and consumed by
# the validation gate. See "H2"-"H5" above for the rationale on each.
FLAGS_PRODUCTION=" \
    -O2 \
    -std=legacy \
    -fno-automatic \
    -finit-local-zero \
    -finit-real=zero \
    -fno-align-commons \
    -ffixed-form \
    -ffixed-line-length-132 \
"

# ----- Audit build flags -----
# Stricter, slower binary used to investigate a specific divergence.
# Not baked into the SIF. Invoke build.sh with FLAVOR=audit.
FLAGS_AUDIT=" \
    -O0 \
    -g \
    -std=legacy \
    -fno-automatic \
    -finit-local-zero \
    -finit-real=zero \
    -fno-align-commons \
    -ffixed-form \
    -ffixed-line-length-132 \
    -fbacktrace \
    -fcheck=all \
    -ffpe-trap=invalid,zero,overflow \
    -Wall \
"

# ----- Output binary -----
# MOVES expects the NONROAD binary at NONROAD/NR08a/NONROAD.exe (the
# .exe suffix is part of the filename MOVES looks up; the file itself
# is a Linux ELF binary on this platform).
NONROAD_BINARY_NAME="NONROAD.exe"

# ----- Known divergences (validation fallback) -----
# When the validation gate (run on HPC compute) finds an equipment
# category that cannot be made fidelity-correct with the flags above,
# record it here as `KNOWN_DIVERGENT_<scc>=` with a one-line note.
# Empty for now -- populated as the validation gate runs.
